## Spoken summary (Aftertone / local TTS)

This workspace uses **Aftertone**: after a coding agent finishes a reply, a hook can **speak one short line** via local TTS. The prepare script prefers explicit text inside `<spoken_summary>...</spoken_summary>` in your **final** assistant message; otherwise it falls back to a short heuristic (often worse for speech).

**Adapters:** Cursor is wired today; Claude / Codex paths may differ — still end substantive replies with the tag when your tool runs the same TTS pipeline.

**When to include the tag**

- Include it for **substantive** answers (explanations, steps, design, debugging, multi-sentence replies).
- **Skip** it for trivial replies (single word, pure ack, “done”, emoji-only).

**What goes inside the tag (this is what gets spoken — nothing else from the reply is chosen)**

- **One** short sentence, as if you were saying it aloud to a busy person walking past.
- Plain language only: **no** markdown, bullets, code, file paths, or URLs inside the tag (URLs are painful when read aloud).
- Summarize **outcome or gist** (“We fixed the hook by adding version one”), not every step.
- Do **not** restate the whole answer; do **not** narrate meta (“here is your summary”).
- Put the block **at the very end** of the message, on its own lines: open tag `<spoken_summary>`, newline, one sentence, newline, close tag `</spoken_summary>`.
- Keep it concise; very long lines are capped by `max_chars` in `speak_summary.toml` (see repo root [AGENTS.md](../../AGENTS.md)).

**Speech-friendly wording (TTS reads text literally)**

- **Expand abbreviations** listeners would say in full: write “for example” not “e.g.”, “that is” not “i.e.”, “and so on” not “etc.”, “versus” not “vs.” when it matters.
- **Avoid Latin shorthand and symbols** that sound wrong or mumbled: prefer “approximately” over “~”, “and” over “&”, “percent” over “%” in the spoken line when clarity matters.
- **Acronyms:** either spell them as words (“text to speech”) or space letters (“T T S”) if you want letter-by-letter; bare “TTS” may be mispronounced.
- **File paths, hashes, ticket IDs** in the tag will be read character-by-character — paraphrase (“the config file”) instead.

## Manual check when the user says “test”

If the user is clearly **checking that spoken TTS works** (e.g. they say **“test”**, “test speech”, “test the hook”, “say something”), **always** end your reply with `<spoken_summary>...</spoken_summary>` containing a **short, distinctive** line they can listen for (for example: “Aftertone speech test, one two three.”). That line is what the hook sends to the daemon, so they can confirm end-to-end without guessing which part of the reply would have been chosen.
